Exercise 5.4: Explain each of the following examples, and correct any
problems you detect.
(a) while (string::iterator iter != s.end()) { /* . . . */ }
(b) while (bool status = find(word)) { /* . . . */ }
if (!status) { /* . . . */ }

Answer:
a)iter is not initialized and thus the expression is illegal.
string::iterator iter = s.begin();
while (iter != s.end()) { /* . . . */ }
b)status is defined inside the while loop so accessing it after the loop is illegal.
bool status;
while (status = find(word)) { /* . . . */ }
if (!status) { /* . . . */ }
